			<ns0:name>eaelt...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/103360015124260446450/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Well, I agree with Victor that detecting that kind of assumption is a nice thing.

From the other hand, if redefining the requirement as "if an arch's plain int is 32-bit, then int32_t must be defined as int" sounds much less scary than "int32_t must be int" and will still detect the problem in case int is not 32-bit.

I think we can approach to the solution from both ends.
I'll check what happens in glibc.
